"Honda M.C.","Biological pump in northwestern North Pacific",2003,"Journal of Oceanography","59","5",,"671","684",,,10.1023/B:JOCE.0000009596.57705.0c,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0345099275&partnerID=40&md5=cac77eb7031dbda09b75606d833dd3c4","Mutsu Institute for Oceanography, Japan Marine Sci./Technology Center, Natsushima, Yokosuka 237-0061, Japan","Honda, M.C., Mutsu Institute for Oceanography, Japan Marine Sci./Technology Center, Natsushima, Yokosuka 237-0061, Japan","The northwestern North Pacific is considered to be one of the most productive areas in the global ocean. Although the marginal zones along the Japanese and Kuril islands, Kamchatka Peninsula, and Aleutian Islands are certainly productive, recent studies do not always show high primary production values in the western subarctic gyre (WSG). In addition, a recent analysis of the biological pump in the WSG showed that, in contrast to what was previously reported, the vertical change of the particulate organic carbon flux with depth is large. Nevertheless, the biological pump in the north-western North Pacific may function to draw down the partial pressure of CO2 in the surface water because the ratio of the organic carbon flux to inorganic carbon flux (Corg/Cinorg), the export flux, and the export ratio from the surface water are higher than those in other oceans. This article also introduces recent research on changes to the biological pump that might have been caused by global warming.","Biogeochemical change; Export flux; Export ratio; Primary production; Vertical change; Western subarctic gyre","biogeochemical cycle; biological pump; organic carbon; particulate flux; primary production; Pacific Ocean",,,,,,"Andreev, A., Kusakabe, M., Honda, M.C., Murata, A., Saito, C., Vertical fluxes of nutrients and carbon through the halocline in the western subarctic gyre calculated by mass balance (2002) Deep-Sea Res. II, 49, pp. 5577-5594; Antia, A.N., Koeve, W., Fischer, G., Blanz, T., 